  "prompt": "Do I need a lawyer prepared NDA when talking to product design & manufacturing consultants? Will a template off the internet work just as well?",
  "response": "When considering whether to use a lawyer-prepared Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA) or an internet template, there are several factors to take into account:\n\n1. **Complexity of Your Situation**: If your project involves sensitive information, proprietary technologies, or unique circumstances, a lawyer can tailor the NDA to your specific needs and ensure it adequately protects your interests.\n\n2. **Template Limitations**: While there are many NDA templates available online, they may not cover all necessary legal aspects or be appropriate for your specific situation. Templates can sometimes be too generic and may not address the nuances of your business relationship or the type of information being shared.\n\n3. **Legal Jurisdiction**: NDAs are governed by state or national laws, and a lawyer can help ensure that the agreement complies with applicable laws in your jurisdiction.\n\n4. **Enforceability**: A lawyer can help draft an NDA that is more likely to be enforceable in court, which is important if a dispute arises.\n\n5. **Clarity and Specificity**: A custom NDA can be clearer and more specific about what constitutes confidential information, the purpose of sharing it, and the duration of the confidentiality obligation.\n\nIf your project is relatively straightforward and the information shared is not highly sensitive, a well-crafted template might suffice. However, for greater peace of mind and legal protection, consulting with a lawyer to draft or review your NDA is often a wise investment, especially in professional relationships involving product design and manufacturing.",
